---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Agent Identity — Eidos AGI"
  description="Agents need their own identity — not a borrowed login, not a shared API key. Real accounts, real credentials, real audit trails."
>
  <div class="page">
    <div class="mark">
      <a href="/">eidos agi</a>
      <div class="mark-right">
        <nav id="nav-menu">
          <a href="/contract-driven-development">methodology</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/eidos-agi">github</a>
          <a href="https://pypi.org/user/eidos-agi/">pypi</a>
        </nav>
        <button class="hamburger" id="hamburger" aria-label="Menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="nav-menu">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5">
            <line x1="3" y1="5" x2="17" y2="5"/>
            <line x1="3" y1="10" x2="17" y2="10"/>
            <line x1="3" y1="15" x2="17" y2="15"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <article class="aid-page">
      <header class="aid-hero">
        <h1>Agent Identity</h1>
        <p class="aid-sub">The security layer the governance stack depends on.</p>
      </header>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>The problem</h2>
        <p>Most AI agents operate under borrowed identity. They use the developer's API key, the team's service account, the company's OAuth token. When the agent makes a request, the system sees the human — not the agent. When something goes wrong, the audit trail points to a person who wasn't there.</p>
        <p>This worked when agents were copilots — tools that helped humans do things. It doesn't work when agents act independently. An agent that deploys code, sends emails, modifies databases, and manages infrastructure needs its own identity. Not a shared credential. Its own.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>The Unix insight</h2>
        <p>Unix solved this 54 years ago. Every process runs as a user. The user has permissions. The permissions are auditable. Root can do anything; regular users can't. When something breaks, you check which user did it.</p>
        <p>AI agents need the same thing: their own user accounts, their own credentials, their own home directories, their own audit trails. The operating system already knows how to separate authority. We're applying that to the agent layer.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>AID — Agent Identity Document</h2>
        <p>An AID is a signed document that establishes who an agent is, what it's authorized to do, and who authorized it. It separates three concerns that are usually tangled together:</p>
        <div class="aid-trio">
          <div class="aid-trio-item">
            <h3>Identity</h3>
            <p>Who is this agent? Not "which API key" but which persistent entity with its own email, its own keys, its own history.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="aid-trio-item">
            <h3>Delegation</h3>
            <p>Who authorized this agent to act? A human principal signs a delegation token scoping what the agent can do, for how long, in which domains.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="aid-trio-item">
            <h3>Verification</h3>
            <p>How does a system verify the agent's authority? 11-step verification: structural validation, signature, expiration, revocation, scope, rate limits, spend, domains, TLS, geo, nonce.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>Hancock — the authorization layer</h2>
        <p>Hancock is the implementation of AID for Eidos. Named for John Hancock — the man whose signature was so large King George could read it without his spectacles. The analogy: authorization should be unambiguous.</p>
        <div class="aid-features">
          <div class="aid-feature">
            <h3>Capability scoping</h3>
            <p>21 capabilities across 7 categories: screen, terminal, HTTP, communication, data, filesystem, financial. Each delegation token specifies exactly which capabilities the agent has.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="aid-feature">
            <h3>Step-up authentication</h3>
            <p>When an agent hits an action that exceeds its current authorization, it requests step-up auth. The human approves via 2FA. The agent gets a time-limited token for that specific action.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="aid-feature">
            <h3>Autonomy gradient</h3>
            <p>Not binary (autonomous vs. supervised). Four levels: 0 (every action approved), 1 (policy-gated), 2 (notification-only), 3 (fully autonomous). Teams dial up autonomy as trust builds.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="aid-feature">
            <h3>Revocation</h3>
            <p>Revoke an agent's access without revoking the human's. Instantly. The delegation token is the unit of revocation, not the credential.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>What an agent gets</h2>
        <p>An Eidos agent has its own:</p>
        <ul class="aid-list">
          <li>Email address (e.g., <code>eidos@eidosagi.com</code>)</li>
          <li>OS user account with home directory</li>
          <li>Cryptographic keypair (Ed25519)</li>
          <li>GitHub account for code contributions</li>
          <li>Delegation tokens scoped per task</li>
          <li>Audit trail — every action attributed to the agent, not the human</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The human authorizes. The agent executes. The system knows the difference.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="aid-section">
        <h2>Status</h2>
        <p>AID Protocol is designed and documented. Hancock is in early implementation. The philosophy, architecture, and capability taxonomy are settled. The dashboard and runtime are being built.</p>
        <p>The governance trilogy (visionlog, research.md, ike.md) is shipped and usable today. Agent identity is the next layer — the security foundation that makes governance enforceable across organizational boundaries.</p>
      </section>
    </article>

    <footer class="foot">
      <span>&copy; {new Date().getFullYear()} Eidos AGI</span>
    </footer>
  </div>

  <script>
    const hb = document.getElementById('hamburger');
    const nm = document.getElementById('nav-menu');
    if (hb && nm) {
      hb.addEventListener('click', () => {
        nm.classList.toggle('open');
        hb.setAttribute('aria-expanded', nm.classList.contains('open'));
      });
      document.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
        if (!hb.contains(e.target) && !nm.contains(e.target)) nm.classList.remove('open');
      });
    }
  </script>
</Base>

<style is:global>
  .aid-page {
    max-width: var(--measure-prose);
  }

  .aid-hero {
    padding: var(--space-16) 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .aid-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, var(--text-4xl));
    line-height: 0.95;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  .aid-sub {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }

  .aid-section {
    padding: var(--space-12) 0;
    border-top: var(--border-width) solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 15%, transparent);
  }
  .aid-section h2 { margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
  .aid-section p {
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .aid-trio {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }
  .aid-trio-item {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  }
  .aid-trio-item h3 {
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  .aid-trio-item p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-muted);
  }

  .aid-features {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }
  .aid-feature {
    padding: var(--space-4) 0;
    border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 10%, transparent);
  }
  .aid-feature h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  .aid-feature p {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-muted);
  }

  .aid-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0;
  }
  .aid-list li {
    padding: var(--space-2) 0;
    border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 8%, transparent);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
  }
  .aid-list li::before {
    content: "— ";
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }
  .aid-list code {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-command);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .aid-trio { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .aid-features { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
</style>
